<section xml:id="S_relations">
  <title>Relations</title>
  <introduction>
    <exploration xml:id="PA_USA">
      <title>The United States of America</title>
      <p>
        Recall from <xref ref="S_cartesian"></xref>
        that the <term>Cartesian product</term>
            <idx><h>Cartesian product</h></idx>
        of two sets <m>A</m> and <m>B</m>,
        written <m>A \times B</m>,
        is the set of all ordered pairs <m>\left( {a,b} \right)</m>,
        where <m>a \in A</m> and <m>b \in B</m>.
        That is, <m>A \times B = \left\{ {\left( {a,b} \right) \mid a \in A\text{ and } b \in B} \right\}</m>.
      </p>
      <p>
        Let <m>A</m> be the set of all states in the United States and let
        <me>
          R = \left\{ { {\left( {x, y} \right) \in A \times A } \mid x \text{  and  } y \text{  have a land border in common } } \right\}\!
        </me>.
      </p>
      <p>
        For example, since California and Oregon have a land border,
        we can say that <m>(\text{ California, Oregon } ) \in R</m> and <m>(\text{ Oregon, California } ) \in R</m>.
        Also, since California and Michigan do not share a land border,
        <m>\text{ (California, Michigan) } \notin R</m> and <m>(\text{ Michigan, California } ) \notin R</m>.
      </p>
      <ol>
        <li>
          <p>
            Use the roster method to specify the elements in each of the following sets:
          </p>
          <ol>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>B = \left\{ {y \in A\left| {\left( {\text{ Michigan, } y} \right) \in R} \right.} \right\}</m>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>C = \left\{ {x \in A\left| {\left( {x,\text{ Michigan } } \right) \in R} \right.} \right\}</m>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>D = \left\{ {y \in A\left| {\left( {\text{ Wisconsin, } y} \right) \in R} \right.} \right\}</m>
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Find two different examples of two ordered pairs,
            <m>\left( {x, y} \right)</m> and
            <m>\left( {y, z} \right)</m> such that <m>\left( {x, y} \right) \in R</m>,
            <m>\left( {y, z} \right) \in R</m>,
            but <m>\left( {x, z} \right)\not \in R</m>,
            or explain why no such example exists.
            Based on this,
            is the following conditional statement true or false?
            For all <m>x, y, z \in A</m>,
            if <m>(x, y) \in R</m> and
            <m>(y, z) \in R</m>, then <m>(x, z) \in R</m>.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Is the following conditional statement true or false?
            Explain.
            For all <m>x, y \in A</m>, if
            <m>(x, y) \in R</m>, then <m>(y, x) \in R</m>.
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </exploration>
    <exploration xml:id="PA_eqn2variables">
      <title>The Solution Set of an Equation with Two Variables</title>
      <p>
        In <xref ref="S_predicates"></xref>,
        we introduced the concept of the
        <term>truth set of an open sentence with one variable</term>.
            <idx><h>truth set</h></idx>
        This was defined to be the set of all elements in the universal set that can be substituted for the variable to make the open sentence a true proposition.
        Assume that <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> represent real numbers.
        Then the equation
        <me>
          4x^2  + y^2  = 16
        </me>
        is an open sentence with two variables.
        An element of the truth set of this open sentence
        (also called a solution of the equation)
        is an ordered pair <m>\left( {a, b} \right)</m> of real numbers so that when <m>a</m> is substituted for <m>x</m> and <m>b</m> is substituted for <m>y</m>,
        the predicate becomes a true statement (a true equation in this case).
        We can use set builder notation to describe the truth set <m>S</m> of this equation with two variables as follows:
        <me>
          S = \left\{ (x, y) \in \R \times \R \mid 4x^2 + y^2 = 16 \right\}\!
        </me>.
      </p>
      <p>
        When a set is a truth set of an open sentence that is an equation,
        we also call the set the <term>solution set</term>
            <idx><h>solution set</h></idx>
        of the equation.
      </p>
      <ol>
        <li>
          <p>
            List four different elements of the set <m>S</m>.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            The graph of the equation <m>4x^2 + y^2 = 16</m> in the <m>xy</m>-coordinate plane is an ellipse.
            Draw the graph and explain why this graph is a representation of the truth set
            (solution set)
            of the equation <m>4x^2 + y^2 = 16</m>.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li xml:id="PA_eqn2variables3">
          <p>
            Describe each of the following sets as an interval of real numbers:
          </p>
          <ol>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>A = \left\{ x \in \R \mid \text{ there exists a } y \in \R \text{ such that } 4x^2 + y^2 = 16 \right\}</m>.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>B = \left\{ y \in \R \mid \text{ there exists an } x \in \R \text{ such that } 4x^2 + y^2 = 16 \right\}</m>.
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </exploration>
  </introduction>
  <subsection>
    <title>Introduction to Relations</title>
    <p>
      In <xref ref="S_introfunctions"></xref>,
      we introduced the formal definition of a function from one set to another set.
      The notion of a function can be thought of as one way of relating the elements of one set with those of another set
      (or the same set).
      A function is a special type of <em>relation</em>
      in the sense that each element of the first set, the domain, is
      <q>related</q>
      to exactly one element of the second set, the codomain.
    </p>
    <p>
      This idea of relating the elements of one set to those of another set using ordered pairs is not restricted to functions.
      For example, we may say that one integer, <m>a</m>,
      is related to another integer, <m>b</m>,
      provided that <m>a</m> is congruent to <m>b</m> modulo 3.
      Notice that this relation of congruence modulo 3 provides a way of relating one integer to another integer.
      However, in this case,
      an integer <m>a</m> is related to more than one other integer.
      For example, since
      <me>
        5 \equiv 5 \pmod 3\!,  5 \equiv 2 \pmod 3\!,  \text{ and }   5 \equiv -1 \pmod 3\!
      </me>,
      we can say that 5 is related to 5, 5 is related to 2, and 5 is related to <m>-1</m>.
      Notice that, as with functions,
      each relation of the form <m>a \equiv b \pmod 3</m> involves two integers <m>a</m> and <m>b</m> and hence involves an ordered pair <m>\left( {a, b} \right)</m>,
      which is an element of <m>\Z \times \Z</m>.
    </p>
    <definition xml:id="relation">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>A</m> and <m>B</m> be sets.
          A <term>relation <term>R</term> from the set</term>
              <idx><h>relation</h></idx>
          <m>\boldsymbol{A}</m> <term>to the set</term>
          <m>\boldsymbol{B}</m> is a subset of <m>A \times B</m>.
          That is, <m>R</m> is a collection of ordered pairs where the first coordinate of each ordered pair is an element of <m>A</m>,
          and the second coordinate of each ordered pair is an element of <m>B</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
          A relation from the set <m>A</m> to the set <m>A</m> is called a
          <term>relation on the set <term>A</term></term>.
          So a relation on the set <m>A</m> is a subset of <m>A \times A</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>
    <p>
      In <xref ref="S_introfunctions"></xref>,
      we defined the domain and range of a function.
      We make similar definitions for a relation.
    </p>
    <definition xml:id="domrangeofrelation">
      <statement>
        <p>
          If <m>R</m> is a relation from the set <m>A</m> to the set <m>B</m>,
          then the subset of <m>A</m> consisting of all the first coordinates of the ordered pairs in <m>R</m> is called the <term>domain</term>
          <idx><h>domain</h><h>of a relation</h></idx>
              <idx><h>relation</h><h>domain</h></idx>
          of <m>R</m>.
          The subset of <m>B</m> consisting of all the second coordinates of the ordered pairs in <m>R</m> is called the <term>range</term>
          <idx><h>range</h><h>of a relation</h></idx>
              <idx><h>relation</h><h>range</h></idx>
          of <m>R</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
          We use the notation <m>\text{ dom } ( R )</m> for the domain of <m>R</m> and
          <m>\text{ range } ( R )</m> for the range of <m>R</m>.
          So using set builder notation,
          <md>
            <mrow>\text{ dom }  ( R )   \amp = \left\{ { {u \in A } \mid \left( {u, y} \right) \in R\text{ for at least one } y \in B} \right\}</mrow>
            <mrow xml:id="sym_rangerel">\text{ range }  ( R ) \amp = \left\{ { {v \in B } \mid \left( {x, v} \right) \in R\text{ for at least one } x \in A} \right\}\!</mrow>
          </md>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>
    <example xml:id="exam_relation">
      <title>Domain and Range</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          A relation was studied in each of the beginning  activities for this section.
          For Beginning  <xref ref="PA_eqn2variables"></xref>,
          the set <m>S = \left\{ (x, y) \in \R \times \R \mid 4x^2 + y^2 = 16 \right\}\!</m> is a subset of <m>\R \times \R</m> and, hence,
          <m>S</m> is a relation on <m>\R</m>.
          In Problem<nbsp/><xref ref="PA_eqn2variables3"/> of Beginning  <xref ref="PA_eqn2variables"></xref>,
          we actually determined the domain and range of this relation.
          <md>
            <mrow>\text{ dom } (S) \amp = A = \left\{ x \in \R \mid \text{ there exists a }  y \in \R \text{ such that }  4x^2 + y^2 = 16 \right\}</mrow>
            <mrow>\text{ range } (S) \amp = B = \left\{ y \in \R \mid \text{ there exists an }  x \in \R \text{ such that }  4x^2 + y^2 = 16 \right\}</mrow>
          </md>
        </p>
        <p>
          So from the results in <xref ref="PA_eqn2variables"></xref>,
          we can say that the domain of the relation <m>S</m> is the closed interval
          <m>\left[ -2, 2 \right]</m> and the range of <m>S</m> is the closed interval <m>\left[ -4, 4 \right]</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </example>
